name: Jaki
about:
Believed to have tenuous connections to the Royal House of Moldavia, Jaki was raised by a group of intelligent hairless chimpanzees in the heart of the Amazon forest, only being discovered one day in her sixteenth year by the famous explorer, Captain R. Burroughs.

Unleashed upon the civilized world by Captain Burroughs, Jaki turned her considerable talents to writing, and her debut book 326 Things to do with a Stuffed and Mounted Michael Flately spent 36 weeks on the New York Times Best Seller List.

A further six books also spent time there, although sadly, her non-fiction book Supermodels Can Act! didn't enjoy much success. Due mainly to the fact that the buying public believed it to be a work of fiction.

It was during this time, that tragedy struck. Bad book sales sent her into a spiral of depression, and it wasn't long before her addiction to '80's Teen Idol, Joey Lawrence, became common knowledge to her adoptive family and friends.

Pushing aside their horror, they sent her to the successful 'Really Bad '80's Teen Idols Addiction Clinic' where amongst the sad tales of Corey Feldman, Adam Ant, Jason Priestly and Michael J Fox addictions, she battled her demons and finally emerged, triumphant.

Part of her therapy included making intimate adult toys with Lego®, a hobby that she has translated into a world-wide successful business.

Jaki is currently working on her autobiography of her time among the apes, tentatively called Life with Danny Bonaduce.

name: Leonardo Arenas
about:
Sonora, México, 1976.
A los siete años de edad llegó a sus manos un ejemplar del Asombroso Hombre Araña, los dibujos, el color y las historias lo cautivaron y dejaron marcado de una manera tan significativa que aún hoy en día es fiel seguidor de ese menospreciado arte llamado cómic.

Al cursar secundaria, se vio envuelto en soldaduras, procesamiento de alimentos, arado de campos, cultivo de miel e incluso el sacrificio de puercos. Aprendió a preparar desde mermelada hasta procesar jamones y carnes frías de alta calidad. Ya en preparatoria, trabajó con microscopios, muestras de sangre y pruebas de laboratorio. Fue parte de un equipo de soccer y estuvo a punto de coronarse rey a causa de un baile y un matraz. Todos esos años jamás dejó de lado el dibujo y los cómics, esto lo llevó a explorar nuevos áreas de lectura, entonces entraron en su mundo personalidades como Borges, Cortázar, Asimov, Scott Card, Tolkien y muchos otros.

Entró a la carrera de Artes Visuales de la Universidad Autónoma de Nuevo León. Sus estudios los alternó con el trabajo por las tardes en una agencia de publicidad y la enseñanza de dibujo a niños. Se graduó y no conforme con ello estudió una maestría en Arte. Tiene la manía de ver mucho cine, leer demasiado, ilustrar y escuchar música mientras trabaja (mucho).

Su tarjeta de presentación dice VP Creativo de una agencia de publicidad, juega mucho Xbox y Playstation.

name: Tracy Cutchlow
about:
I'm the author of Zero to Five: 70 Essential Parenting Tips Based on Science (and What I've Learned So Far). It's a beautifully photographed collection of foundational tips for first-time parents, on everything from talking with baby to sleeping and eating to discipline.

I've been an editor most of my life: newspaper editor, book editor, personal-finance editor, managing editor. After editing the bestsellers Brain Rules and Brain Rules for Baby, I worked on the coolest cookbooks ever, Modernist Cuisine and Modernist Cuisine at Home. Then I had a charming little baby. Now I'm mostly a stay-at-home mom ... and an author.

I'm a city girl who loves the outdoors. I hike and bike as often as I can. I've lived in Portland, Madison, Boston, and San Francisco, but I always come home to Seattle.

My book on Goodreads: Zero to Five: 70 Essential Parenting Tips Based on Science (and What I've Learned So Far).

Subscribe to my newsletter of parenting tips: www.zerotofive.net

Hope to hear from you!

name: Athena
about:
My blog at aquatique.net features my books read and reviewed.

I use to be one of those kids who spent my summers reading books from the library. My love of literature was definitely one of my first.

Here is the rationale for the star rating system here on GR:
5 stars: I love it and want to reread/own it
4 stars: I really like it or love it
3 stars: I liked it with some caveats.
2 stars: It is OK, average, or below average.
1 star: I did not like it.

My listing of read books is mostly up to date from 2002 to the present. I only started listing the dates of books read in 2012. Many of the books I read for uni and grad school are not listed though as I forgot most of them.

Shelves are used to list books read each year and favourite books from certain genres for reference to future buying or recommendations.

Please feel free to add me or say hello.

Profile Picture is La Liseuse (A Young Girl Reading or The Reader) by Jean-Honoré Fragonard.
